result.execSummary:
All charges against Ebonie Nicole Crumpton in this case have been dismissed. These charges were not proven and have no legal effect. Ebonie Nicole Crumpton is presumed innocent.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

Defendant Ebonie Nicole Crumpton appeared by video.  Attorney Allison Marie Ritter appeared by video for Ebonie Nicole Crumpton.  
Prosecuting attorney Olivia Simmons appeared by video for the State of Wisconsin. 
Deputy Court Clerk: rmm. 
Matter set for status conference.  State informed the Court the victim is deceased.  On motion of the state, Court ordered case dismissed.

Defendant Ebonie Nicole Crumpton in court.  Prosecuting attorney Michael J. Odden in court for the State of Wisconsin. Hearing held via zoom. Indigency hearing proceeded.  Court makes a finding that defendant is indigent.  Court appoints Allison Ritter as counsel for defendant at the rate of $100.00 per hour.  Attorney Ritter accepts appointment.  Defendant shall reimburse Milwaukee County at the rate of $75.00 on the 1st of every month, commencing 10/01/2022 until paid in full. Failure to pay will result in a civil judgment and/or tax intercept or other means. Case is adjourned in Branch 01. This case will be heard via Zoom. Zoom meeting information provided to parties.
Status conference scheduled for September 19, 2022 at 09:30 am.
